Hardscape & Exterior Specialties
These trades mirror your landscaping logic but often require higher-precision material tracking (like stone or metal).
Fencing & Decking Contractors: They need to calculate linear footage, post spacing, and hardware counts (screws, brackets, concrete bags).
Paving & Driveway Specialists: High-cost materials (asphalt, pavers, crushed stone) require exact square footage and depth calculations.
Pool & Spa Installers: They involve complex excavation volumes and multi-stage plumbing/electrical estimates.
General Landscapers: They involve multiple plants, sprinkler systems, grass, rock, and more.
Interior Finish & Surface Trades
These trades are highly visual and require precise waste-factor calculations for expensive materials.
Flooring Installers: Calculating tile, hardwood, or LVP with a "waste percentage" (usually 10–15%) is a core pain point you can solve.
Cabinetry & Millwork: Estimating linear feet of trim, crown molding, and the labor for custom cabinetry installation.
Countertop Fabricators: Estimating slab usage based on square footage, including cutouts for sinks and edge treatments.
Systems & Structural Trades
These trades focus less on aesthetics and more on "runs" (linear feet of wire or pipe) and "fixtures."
HVAC Technicians: Estimating ductwork runs, unit sizing (BTUs), and refrigerant line sets.
Drywall & Insulation Contractors: Calculating sheet counts, joint compound needs, and R-value material thickness.
Solar Panel Installers: Estimating rack systems based on roof pitch and electrical conduit runs.

